{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"ea5deda3-2082-4e82-9e86-49535c9f9f1d","agentId":"afa5e38c6946052d0","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Do focused WEB research (WebSearch + WebFetch; cite URLs) to inform a design decision for a local self-evolving agent (\"Yogi\") on a 16 GB Apple Silicon Mac. Do not answer from memory alone.\n\nDECISION: should the agent's primary \"compounding\" (getting measurably better over time, model held constant) come from TOKEN-SPACE mechanisms — (a) episodic→semantic memory consolidation and (b) embedding-based retrieval (local RAG with `nomic-embed-text`) — rather than weight training, given the 16 GB budget makes on-device fine-tuning marginal?\n\nResearch and answer:\n1. **Evidence that memory consolidation + retrieval alone yield measurable, growing task performance over time** with the model fixed. Look for memory-augmented agent benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval), long-term-memory agent systems (e.g. Mem0, MemGPT/Letta, A-MEM, EverMemOS), and any results quantifying improvement attributable to memory vs none.\n2. **How much of \"compounding\" is realistically achievable from memory/retrieval vs weight distillation?** Is \"continual learning in token space\" (memory + retrieved context + skill/prompt updates) a credible primary mechanism, per recent practice? (Letta and others have argued this.)\n3. **Practical local RAG details for `nomic-embed-text`:** embedding dimension, similarity (cosine) + hybrid/BM25, recency/freshness weighting, chunking, and common failure modes (stale memory, retrieval drift).\n4. **Sequencing:** for a 16 GB on-device research build, should M3 LEAD with token-space compounding (consolidation + retrieval — cheap, no training) and treat per-domain weight distillation as a secondary/optional foreground arm gated behind it?\n\nEND WITH a concrete RECOMMENDATION for Yogi M3: whether to make token-space (consolidation + retrieval) the primary compounding mechanism the bench measures first, and how to structure it. Cite URLs throughout. Return findings only; do not edit files."},"uuid":"d761cd91-fe5c-4c0c-8825-049c35602ed1","timestamp":"2026-06-21T03:46:28.666Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
